<br>
First; Monks, Rogues, and Bards are the three classes that make up the collective known as &quot;The Rogues&quot;.<br>
<br>
Second; Rangers fall in the collective known as &quot;The Hybrids&quot;.  This includes Shadow Knights, Paladins, and Rangers.  These hybrids are all derivatives of the &quot;Warrior&quot; IE the grand dady tank.<br>
<br>
Rogues were not designed to be tanks.  They can function in this capacity, should the need arise, however they will generally speaking require alot of help doing this.  Whether that be extreme twinking, or extreme buffing / caster support.<br>
<br>
Bard's lose effectivness in a MT situation due to the fact that you cannot reliably twist 4 songs when you are being pounded upon and stunned constantly.  The most MY bard has been able to twist while soloing is usualy about two songs with no instrument switching.  This is due to the fact that Bards have almost 0 avoidance AC ... nearly all Bard AC is mitigation.  This means that although Bards tend to take less damage from hits, they get hit alot (hence they are stunded easy, interupting songs).  This also means that if a Bard is tanking more than one opponent, the Bard WILL NOT last long.<br>
<br>
Rogues lose effectivness in a MT situation due to the fact that rogues must be behind an oponent to BS, which is their primary damage source, especially at higher levels.  Although I know many people think rogues are taunt machines (and they are), once you remove BS from that equation a large part of their taunt factor is removed, and they may not be able to hold it (aggro).  Also if a rogue evades while he is MT, your group will likley die, since the mob wont default back to a warrior or such, but rather a caster.  On the plus side Rogues have a balance between mitigation / avoidance AC, however they are still inferior to an equivalent warrior/derivative.<br>
<br>
Monks have very little mitigation AC ... nearly all Monk AC is avoidance.  This means that although they will get hit less, they tend to get hit for MORE damage per hit.  This combined with naturally low hp means trouble.  A properly twinked and caster supported monk is actually a quite effective tank, but a properly equiped and caster supported warrior/derivative is EVEN more effective.<br>
<br>
&quot;The Rogues&quot; (the collective) recive much less HP per level than warriors/derivatives.  This becomes more of an issue post 50 when warrior/derivatives HP scale upwards, while Rogues remain constant.<br>
<br>
Why did I type all this?  Because your post (the original post) gives the impression that Rangers are on the same level as &quot;The Rogues&quot; in terms of tanking ability.  Now I am the first to say Rangers are not the most effective tanks, later in the game, when compared to Warriors, SKs, and Pallys ...<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>     But Rangers are still warrior derivatives, and all things equal will out tank a Rogue 100% of the time, with less upport work required from the group.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Rangers get stigma because they are the least twinked class on blue servers, and an untwinked anything compared to an uber twinked anything <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>     ALWAYS</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> looks inferior.<br>
<br>
P.S. I have played a Monk to 60, and have soloed at 60.  If you pick me over a similarly equiped Ranger at level 60 to be YOUR tank, I dont want to be in YOUR group <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START >: --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/mad.gif ALT=">:"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->     .<br>
<br>
It may seem harsh, but the madness must stop.<br>
